Loan Data from Prosper Exploration¶

by Ediong Alexander¶

Introduction¶

The dataset contains information on 113937 loan listings from Prosper, a loan company from 9th November, 2005 to 10th March, 2014. The dataset is made up of 81 columns containing information such as the listing keys, the date the loan was listed, loan status, etc. I will be exploring this dataset to derive insights.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contained of 113,937 rows, 81 columns. The dataset contains 113,937 unique loan listings with zero duplicates.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm especially interested in finding out the factors that affect loan status. Like, are people with a certain employment status more likely to default on loans? Does a certain category of borrowers tend to default on their loans? I'm also interested in finding out factors that affect borrowers APR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I'll be looking into 15 features which include: 'ListingKey', 'ListingCreationDate', 'Term', 'LoanStatus' ,'IncomeRange', 'BorrowerAPR', 'BorrowerRate', 'LenderYield', 'EstimatedReturn', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'ListingCategory (numeric)', 'EmploymentStatus', 'CurrentDelinquencies', 'AmountDelinquent', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', and 'OnTimeProsperPayments'

I'll be selecting columns of interest to reduce the size of the dataset

Charged off loans are defaulted loans in which the lender has given up all hope of recovering. So, I'm going to merge it into defaulted loans to simplify the plot. Also, I am going to merge all past due loans together.

In [14]:
a = []
complete = ['Completed', 'Current','Cancelled' ,'FinalPaymentInProgress']
for stat in df['LoanStatus']:
    if stat in complete:
        a.append(stat)
    elif stat == 'Defaulted' or stat == 'Chargedoff':
        a.append('Defaulted')
    else:
        a.append("Past Due")
df['LoanStatus_m'] = a
In [15]:
sns.countplot(data=df, y='LoanStatus_m', color=sns.color_palette()[0], order=df['LoanStatus_m'].value_counts().index)
plt.title('Loan Status (count)');

From this plot, we can see more clearly that majority of the loans are Current, followed by Completed Loans then defaulted and past due. Further on, I'll look more closely at defaulted loans and past due loans.

Lets now into the prosper rating. Prosper rating is a rating assigned to each loan gotten from Prosper. The rating represents an estimated average annualized loss rate range. "The estimated loss rate is based on the historical performance of Prosper loans with similar characteristics". Below is a table that represents the ratings and average annual loss range gotten from the prosper website.

Prosper Rating Estimated Avg. Annual Loss Rate**
AA 0.00-1.99%
A 2.00–3.99%
B 4.00–5.99%
C 6.00–8.99%
D 9.00–11.99%
E 12.00–14.99%
HR ≥ 15.00%

We can see from the plot above that majority of the borrowers fall into the C category with an estimated annual loss rate of 6.00–8.99%. The plot is also normally distributed with the two extreme categories possessing the least counts.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Question 1: What are the factors that affect Loan status?¶

i. How does employment status affect Loan status (default)?¶

To answer this question, lets plot a clustered countplot of loan status and Employment status

In [20]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 7))
sns.countplot(data=df, x='LoanStatus_m', hue='EmploymentStatus')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('Count of Loan Status showing Employment status')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status');

From the plot we can see that majority of loan defaulters in the dataset are fulltime workers followed by employed While past due is barely seen. Lets subset the dataset for where loan status is past due or defaulted to plot so we can see more clearly.

In [21]:
default = df[df['LoanStatus_m'].isin(['Defaulted', 'Past Due'])]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.countplot(data=default, x='LoanStatus_m', hue='EmploymentStatus')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status');

In the above visualization, we can see more clearly that majority of people whose loans are past due are employed. But is it that employed people tend to be defaulters or fail to payup thier loans on time or are they just the majority in the dataset leading to their larger count? Lets look into this. To do this I'm going to create a dataframe of employment status and the percent of defaulters including those whose loans have past due.

In [22]:
d = default['EmploymentStatus'].value_counts()

    a.append(i)

With the above visualization we can see that although we had a large number of employed people who had defaulted on their loans as shown in the previous visualizations, it was was merely because of their large proportion in the dataset. The visual above shows that about 40% of persons whose employment status were unavailable defaulted on their loans, followed by retired with about 30% and not employed with also about 30%.

So, to answer our question we can say that employment status does affect loan status. As the chart above clearly that most employed people pay up their loans

ii. Does a higher Annual Percentage Rate (APR) contribute to loan default?¶

To answer this question, I'll make use of a boxplot

In [27]:
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='LoanStatus_m', y='BorrowerAPR',color=sns.color_palette()[0])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('Borrower APR vs Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Loan Status')
plt.xlabel('Borrower APR');

From the above visual, we can see that the median APR of defaulted loans and loans past due is higher with the APR at almost 30%. It can be said that a high APR can lead to a borrower not being able to pay up their loans in time hence paying past due or even defaulting on the loan.

Let us go ahead to visualize the relationship between Borrower Rate (Interest Rate) and Loan status. The APR is different from the Interest rate because while interest rate is the percentage of interest paid on a loan, APR includes the interest rate as well as any additional fees or expenses you'll pay to your lender.

In [28]:
sns.violinplot(data=df, x='LoanStatus_m', y='BorrowerRate', color=sns.color_palette()[0])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

Question 2: What are the factors that affect Borrower APR?¶

i. Does the APR increase with Income?¶

To answer this question, I will make use of a boxplot.

In [31]:
order=['Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+', 'Not displayed']
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='IncomeRange', y='BorrowerAPR', order=order,color=sns.color_palette()[0])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR')
plt.xlabel('Income Range')
plt.title('Borrower APR vs Income Range');

Above, we can see that median Borrower APR decreases with increase in Income. Therefore, APR does not increase with income. Rather it tends to decrease as income increases.

iii. Does the prosper rating affect the APR?¶

Lets answer this question by plotting a barchart

In [32]:
sns.barplot(x=df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'], y=df['BorrowerAPR'], order=['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR'], ci=None,color=sns.color_palette()[0])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('Borrower APR vs Prosper Rating')
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR')
plt.xlabel('Prosper Rating');

From the above visual it is clear that borrower APR increases as the estimated average annualized loss rate range increases. Listings rated AA which represents the lowest risk has lower mean APR while HR the highest risk has the highest APR. So the higher estimated average annualized loss rate range the higher the APR.

How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Through our investigation, we were able to find that Defaulted loans has higher APR, Borrower rate and lender yield. It was also found to have high current delinquencies. APR was found to have a negative relationship with Income, and a positive relationship with prosper rating, borrower rate, lender yield, and estimated yield.

Lets look at the correlation between our variables of interest. To do this, I'll have to encode string variables as numbers. I'll begin by replacing "Not displayed" in IncomeRange column with NaN and also replacing "Not available" in EmploymentStatus column with NaN.

In [37]:
df_corr['IncomeRange'] = df_corr['IncomeRange'].replace('Not displayed', np.nan)
df_corr['EmploymentStatus'] = df_corr['EmploymentStatus'].replace('Not available', np.nan)

Now, I'll create ordered lists of categories in LoanStatus, IncomeRange, ProsperRating and EmploymentStatus. I'll then write a function that uses this list to replace the content with the index.

In [38]:
#Ordered arrays used in encoding variables
loan_status = ['Cancelled', 'Current', 'Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Past Due', 'Defaulted']
income_range = ['Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+']
prosper_rating = ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR']
employment_status = ['Not employed', 'Other', 'Part-time', 'Retired', 'Self-employed', 'Employed', 'Full-time']
In [39]:
#Function to encode categories
def cat (arr, col):
    for i in range(len(arr)):
        df_corr[col].replace(arr[i], i, inplace=True)
In [40]:
# Calling functions
cat(loan_status, 'LoanStatus_m')
cat(income_range, 'IncomeRange')
cat(prosper_rating, 'ProsperRating (Alpha)')
cat(employment_status, 'EmploymentStatus')

Conclusion¶

In this Analysis, I was interested in finding out factors that affect the loan status particularly defaulted loans and also factors that affect the borrowers APR. The dataset used for this analysis was clean so much wrangling operations were not carried out. To answer the questions I posed, I made use of various charts like barcharts, histograms, box plots, etc. I was able to come up with the following conclusions:

  1. Most of the loan listings in the dataset was for debt consolidation.
  2. Defaulted loans are associated with high APR. This was further investigated to find that the higher the Estimated Avg. Annual Loss Rate which is represented by Prosper ratings, the higher the APR. So loans with high APR are high risk loans.
  3. Individuals with higher and stable income received lower APR on their loans.
  4. Most employed individuals do not default on their loans.
